abstract: “The whole city had a very frantic feel about it,” one resident said after waters swamped several blocks of downtown Davenport.
snippet: “The whole city had a very frantic feel about it,” one resident said after waters swamped several blocks of downtown Davenport.
lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — For weeks, residents of Davenport, Iowa, looked warily toward the flooded Mississippi River as it encroached on their downtown, the water kept at bay only by temporary barriers lining the street.
headline_main: Floodwaters Swept Into Davenport, Iowa, Sending Residents Scrambling
byline_original: By Mitch Smith and Julie Bosman

abstract: As income inequality becomes a central issue for Democrats, two plans offered by Mr. Booker and Ms. Harris offer a proxy of the battle between them.
snippet: As income inequality becomes a central issue for Democrats, two plans offered by Mr. Booker and Ms. Harris offer a proxy of the battle between them.
lead_paragraph: LONDONDERRY, N.H. — On his third trip to New Hampshire recently, Senator Cory Booker had a new and very specific focus: his “baby bonds” proposal to combat income inequality by giving every child a government-funded savings account.

headline_main: A Green New Deal? L.A. Now Has One

abstract: In amassing a small fortune, the South Bend mayor has had the backing of an exuberant L.G.B.T. donor base. But relying on wealthy contributors carries political risk.
snippet: In amassing a small fortune, the South Bend mayor has had the backing of an exuberant L.G.B.T. donor base. But relying on wealthy contributors carries political risk.
lead_paragraph: Barely two months ago, when Pete Buttigieg, the mayor of South Bend, Ind., was rating no higher than 1 or 2 percent in national polls, he had a well-worn punch line he used as he pitched himself in living rooms and conference rooms where many of the guests were, like him, young, male and gay.

abstract: In Ohio, where companies like FirstEnergy and Goodyear pay no federal corporate taxes, Democrats haven’t figured out how to leverage anxiety over income inequality to defeat President Trump.
snippet: In Ohio, where companies like FirstEnergy and Goodyear pay no federal corporate taxes, Democrats haven’t figured out how to leverage anxiety over income inequality to defeat President Trump.
lead_paragraph: AKRON, Ohio — Colin Robertson wonders why he pays federal taxes on the $18,000 a year he makes cleaning carpets, while the tech giant Amazon got a tax rebate.

abstract: Despite doubts about his candidacy, Joe Biden begins the race with substantial support from three key constituencies in his native state, a place the Democrats can’t afford to lose again.

lead_paragraph: PITTSBURGH — The case for Joseph R. Biden Jr. has always come down to Pennsylvania.

abstract: Mr. Buttigieg will now refuse contributions from federal lobbyists and will return $30,250 to 39 individuals, his campaign said.
snippet: Mr. Buttigieg will now refuse contributions from federal lobbyists and will return $30,250 to 39 individuals, his campaign said.
lead_paragraph: Pete Buttigieg, whose upstart presidential campaign has benefited from an early surge of donations and national attention, will no longer accept contributions from federal lobbyists, his campaign said Friday, bowing to pressure from fellow Democrats who want to reform the way campaigns raise money.

headline_main: Pete Buttigieg Swears Off the Lobbyist Money He Once Accepted
byline_original: By Jeremy W. Peters and Shane Goldmacher

abstract: Mr. Biden raised more in his first 24 hours than any other candidate, easing concerns among some supporters over his ability to raise money.
snippet: Mr. Biden raised more in his first 24 hours than any other candidate, easing concerns among some supporters over his ability to raise money.
lead_paragraph: Joseph R. Biden Jr.’s presidential campaign announced Friday that it had raised $6.3 million in its opening 24 hours, surpassing the first-day totals of his rivals and easing concerns among some supporters over whether he would be able to compete financially in the Democratic primary.
